So thank you for having us.

00:00:13.170 --> 00:00:15.210
We're excited to be here.

00:00:15.210 --> 00:00:19.410
This is actually our second
Google cooking demonstration.

00:00:19.410 --> 00:00:21.380
So for those of you who
haven't been to one,

00:00:21.380 --> 00:00:22.500
we have been to one.

00:00:22.500 --> 00:00:23.670
They're amazing, OK?

00:00:23.670 --> 00:00:26.120
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:27.390 --> 00:00:27.890
Yeah.

00:00:27.890 --> 00:00:30.590
So like you said,
we own Rich Table.

00:00:30.590 --> 00:00:33.890
We opened it about six and a
half, almost seven years ago.

00:00:33.890 --> 00:00:35.840
And it was just kind
of the restaurant

00:00:35.840 --> 00:00:39.590
that we wanted to eat in and
the way that we wanted to dine.

00:00:39.590 --> 00:00:44.510
So we've spent our lives working
in these really fine dining

00:00:44.510 --> 00:00:47.670
restaurants that are super
serious about food, got

00:00:47.670 --> 00:00:49.220
to get dressed up
to work in there,

00:00:49.220 --> 00:00:52.580
and we never really felt that
comfortable going to eat there.

00:00:52.580 --> 00:00:55.430
We loved cooking and thinking
about food in that way,

00:00:55.430 --> 00:00:59.300
but the dining style
was just not really us.

00:00:59.300 --> 00:01:02.450
I mean, I'm not the
most elegant person, OK?

00:01:02.450 --> 00:01:03.275
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:03.275 --> 00:01:04.900
SARAH RICH: What are
you talking about?

00:01:04.900 --> 00:01:07.250
EVAN RICH: But with Rich
Table, we opened it up,

00:01:07.250 --> 00:01:10.790
and it's more of a casual
kind of atmosphere, come

00:01:10.790 --> 00:01:11.930
dressed how you are.

00:01:11.930 --> 00:01:13.820
We bought an old
barn in Petaluma

00:01:13.820 --> 00:01:16.980
and put it all over the
walls, made tables out of it.

00:01:16.980 --> 00:01:21.770
And then we just kind
of cook what we crave.

00:01:21.770 --> 00:01:23.880
We like to say we cook
with our stomachs.

00:01:23.880 --> 00:01:25.940
So we change our
menu pretty often.

00:01:25.940 --> 00:01:27.710
And anytime you
come in and see us,

00:01:27.710 --> 00:01:31.640
you'll see the stuff we've
eaten on our days off.

00:01:31.640 --> 00:01:34.490
So we'll do Korean stuff, we'll
do Chinese, we'll do French,

00:01:34.490 --> 00:01:37.640
we'll do Japanese,
whatever we kind of feel,

00:01:37.640 --> 00:01:40.130
and we'll just kind
of put our take on it.

00:01:40.130 --> 00:01:42.290
People ask us what kind
of restaurant it is,

00:01:42.290 --> 00:01:44.822
and we just say, we go to the
market, we see what's good,

00:01:44.822 --> 00:01:46.280
we cook it, and
let our backgrounds

00:01:46.280 --> 00:01:48.680
speak for themselves.

00:01:48.680 --> 00:01:51.590
Before we were open, that
was a really difficult thing

00:01:51.590 --> 00:01:53.886
for people to grasp onto
when they asked, oh, you're

00:01:53.886 --> 00:01:55.760
opening a restaurant,
what kind of restaurant

00:01:55.760 --> 00:01:56.690
are you opening up?

00:01:56.690 --> 00:01:59.030
And it was just kind
of like, I don't know--

00:01:59.030 --> 00:01:59.690
SARAH RICH: Food restaurant.

00:01:59.690 --> 00:02:01.481
EVAN RICH: --we're
going to cook good food.

00:02:01.481 --> 00:02:04.490
And they were like,
huh, interesting, OK.

00:02:04.490 --> 00:02:06.390
We'll have to check that out.

00:02:06.390 --> 00:02:08.240
SARAH RICH: PR
people don't really

00:02:08.240 --> 00:02:09.544
like that kind of an answer.

00:02:09.544 --> 00:02:11.162
EVAN RICH: Yeah.

00:02:11.162 --> 00:02:12.620
So being in the
Bay Area, there are

00:02:12.620 --> 00:02:14.750
a ton of vegetables,
ton of great products.

00:02:14.750 --> 00:02:17.090
So we try and keep things
as simple as possible,

00:02:17.090 --> 00:02:21.110
because it's real easy
to make delicious food.

00:02:21.110 --> 00:02:23.780
It's difficult to
keep it simple.

00:02:23.780 --> 00:02:26.630
We're chefs, so making
things really chefy

00:02:26.630 --> 00:02:28.310
is pretty easy for us.

00:02:28.310 --> 00:02:30.290
But once you sit
down and eat it,

00:02:30.290 --> 00:02:32.927
it's kind of like, eh,
this is a little too much,

00:02:32.927 --> 00:02:34.010
I'm not really getting it.

00:02:34.010 --> 00:02:36.980
So the challenge for
us is kind of embracing

00:02:36.980 --> 00:02:39.170
what the farmers cook out
here, keeping it simple,

00:02:39.170 --> 00:02:41.420
but still making it
interesting enough

00:02:41.420 --> 00:02:43.982
to have people come to our
restaurant every night.

00:02:43.982 --> 00:02:44.690
SARAH RICH: Yeah.

00:02:44.690 --> 00:02:47.541
And I would say, listening to
all the really lovely things

00:02:47.541 --> 00:02:49.040
you had to say about
the restaurant,

00:02:49.040 --> 00:02:52.849
it made me think about
seven years ago when

00:02:52.849 --> 00:02:54.890
we were trying to put this
idea together and open

00:02:54.890 --> 00:02:56.510
this restaurant, we had no idea.

00:02:56.510 --> 00:02:58.220
You know, we had hopes
and dreams for it,

00:02:58.220 --> 00:03:01.280
but we had no idea that it
would become what it is.

00:03:01.280 --> 00:03:04.010
And we're really proud
and excited that we

00:03:04.010 --> 00:03:06.920
have been able to
create this restaurant

00:03:06.920 --> 00:03:08.460
that people really enjoy.

00:03:08.460 --> 00:03:10.190
And so the cookbook
itself really

00:03:10.190 --> 00:03:12.650
tells the story of how we
created the restaurant.

00:03:12.650 --> 00:03:14.120
It's not just a book of recipes.

00:03:14.120 --> 00:03:17.990
It tells the story of how we
met in New York, fell in love,

00:03:17.990 --> 00:03:21.436
decided to take a chance on
California and move out here,

00:03:21.436 --> 00:03:23.310
had a couple of kids
and opened a restaurant.

00:03:23.310 --> 00:03:25.880
So I think there's a lot in
there that you can read about

00:03:25.880 --> 00:03:28.260
and really relate to as well.

00:03:28.260 --> 00:03:30.980
And so the recipes
in the book really

00:03:30.980 --> 00:03:35.110
comprise the first maybe two or
three years that we were open.

00:03:35.110 --> 00:03:37.220
And in that period
of time, we were

00:03:37.220 --> 00:03:39.612
drawing from a lot of
personal influences,

00:03:39.612 --> 00:03:41.570
whether it's restaurants
that we had worked in,

00:03:41.570 --> 00:03:45.890
chefs we had worked with,
or family memories, which

00:03:45.890 --> 00:03:50.840
is exactly where this
recipe came from.

00:03:50.840 --> 00:03:55.220
Evan's grandmother was
Austrian and would make

00:03:55.220 --> 00:03:56.861
a big Austrian meal on Sundays.

00:03:56.861 --> 00:03:58.610
EVAN RICH: Sauerbraten
and potato pancakes

00:03:58.610 --> 00:03:59.285
every other Sunday.

00:03:59.285 --> 00:04:00.280
It was the most amazing.

00:04:00.280 --> 00:04:01.760
SARAH RICH: They would do
Sunday supper together.

00:04:01.760 --> 00:04:03.860
EVAN RICH: I was very
young so the sauerbraten

00:04:03.860 --> 00:04:05.910
was a little weird to me.

00:04:05.910 --> 00:04:08.840
But the potato pancakes dressed
with butter, and sour cream,

00:04:08.840 --> 00:04:10.310
and applesauce were like--

00:04:10.310 --> 00:04:12.200
I mean, I can
taste it right now,

00:04:12.200 --> 00:04:14.360
it's the most amazing thing.

00:04:14.360 --> 00:04:16.954
The funny thing
about the book is,

00:04:16.954 --> 00:04:19.339
it took us about
three years to make.

00:04:19.339 --> 00:04:23.660
So realistically, 90% of
those recipes in the book, we

00:04:23.660 --> 00:04:25.550
don't actually do at
the restaurant anymore.

00:04:25.550 --> 00:04:28.070
Because we take
versions of it and we're

00:04:28.070 --> 00:04:29.760
always changing and evolving.

00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:31.850
And so people come in now
and they're like, hey,

00:04:31.850 --> 00:04:33.620
I want to try the
sweet potato pancake.

00:04:33.620 --> 00:04:38.180
We're like, well, we got version
12 of the potato pancake,

00:04:38.180 --> 00:04:39.680
how about you try this one?

00:04:39.680 --> 00:04:43.520
But I like to think of the book
as a tool for everyone else

00:04:43.520 --> 00:04:48.020
to have some great ideas and
then put your own take on, put

00:04:48.020 --> 00:04:48.990
your own spin on it.

00:04:48.990 --> 00:04:51.890
So the recipes are
really honed in

00:04:51.890 --> 00:04:53.900
and the flavors are
nice and balanced.

00:04:53.900 --> 00:04:57.090
And it makes it easy for you
guys to execute this stuff.

00:04:57.090 --> 00:04:58.840
But as you'll see when
I make this recipe,

00:04:58.840 --> 00:05:00.214
we'll kind of give
you some ideas

00:05:00.214 --> 00:05:03.410
of how to make it your own,
or how to put your spin on it,

00:05:03.410 --> 00:05:06.150
or how to just have fun with it.

00:05:06.150 --> 00:05:10.140
So everyone always asks,
oh, what recipe did you use,

00:05:10.140 --> 00:05:10.640
so-and-so?

00:05:10.640 --> 00:05:12.780
And you're kind of like, I
don't know, we just kind of cook

00:05:12.780 --> 00:05:14.154
and then we put
together recipes.

00:05:14.154 --> 00:05:16.920
So these are good
baselines for everyone

00:05:16.920 --> 00:05:20.880
to put together a good
repertoire of fun things

00:05:20.880 --> 00:05:22.770
you can cook at home.

00:05:22.770 --> 00:05:25.020
So today we're going to make
the sweet potato pancake.

00:05:25.020 --> 00:05:27.990
So my lovely wife over here
is going to start the potato

00:05:27.990 --> 00:05:29.130
pancake, OK?

00:05:29.130 --> 00:05:30.930
So my grandmother
used to make them

00:05:30.930 --> 00:05:32.910
which just russet
potatoes, but today we're

00:05:32.910 --> 00:05:34.535
going to make them
with sweet potatoes.

00:05:34.535 --> 00:05:37.060
So this is kind of
our version of it.

00:05:37.060 --> 00:05:37.780
SARAH RICH: Yeah.

00:05:37.780 --> 00:05:40.470
So I don't know if
any of you have ever

00:05:40.470 --> 00:05:43.260
made potato pancakes, or latkas,
or anything like that before,

00:05:43.260 --> 00:05:45.330
but it's basically
the same sort of idea

00:05:45.330 --> 00:05:47.490
just using the sweet
potato instead.

00:05:47.490 --> 00:05:49.830
So it'll have a little bit,
obviously kind of a sweeter

00:05:49.830 --> 00:05:53.250
flavor, not so potatoey?

00:05:53.250 --> 00:05:56.100
I don't know, for a
lack of a better--

00:05:56.100 --> 00:05:58.860
so I've just got a regular box
grater, which you probably all

00:05:58.860 --> 00:06:00.150
have access to.

00:06:00.150 --> 00:06:01.800
And I've got my sweet potatoes.

00:06:01.800 --> 00:06:06.010
These were really
pretty gigantic ones.

00:06:06.010 --> 00:06:09.299
So they're cut smaller to
make it a little bit easier.

00:06:09.299 --> 00:06:10.590
And I'm just going to grate it.

00:06:13.390 --> 00:06:16.329
Just be careful of your fingers.

00:06:16.329 --> 00:06:18.370
EVAN RICH: So we're doing
it with sweet potatoes,

00:06:18.370 --> 00:06:21.460
but go to the market, see
what potatoes are available

00:06:21.460 --> 00:06:22.880
and use those.

00:06:22.880 --> 00:06:26.990
So white potatoes,
little creamer potatoes,

00:06:26.990 --> 00:06:28.520
any kind of potato you want.

00:06:28.520 --> 00:06:31.660
And you can even go as far
as like, oh cool it's winter,

00:06:31.660 --> 00:06:33.910
they have a bunch of root
vegetables, I have kohlrabi,

00:06:33.910 --> 00:06:38.380
I have radishes, I
have daikon radish.

00:06:38.380 --> 00:06:43.030
Something that kind of
looks like a root vegetable

00:06:43.030 --> 00:06:45.460
like this, you can
make this cake with.

00:06:45.460 --> 00:06:48.587
So this is an ingredient you can
kind of mix and match and make

00:06:48.587 --> 00:06:49.420
it your own as well.

00:06:51.940 --> 00:06:55.210
With my grandmother's version,
she also did the potato

00:06:55.210 --> 00:06:58.780
and then took a Vidalia onion
and grated it the same way

00:06:58.780 --> 00:07:01.660
and mixed it all up, just
to bring another level

00:07:01.660 --> 00:07:02.680
of sweetness to it.

00:07:02.680 --> 00:07:05.140
But with the sweet
potato, the sweetness

00:07:05.140 --> 00:07:08.710
is there, so we excluded the
onion so it isn't overly sweet.

00:07:10.874 --> 00:07:11.790
SARAH RICH: All right.

00:07:11.790 --> 00:07:14.860
So I'm just going to throw
the sweet potato into a bowl.

00:07:19.181 --> 00:07:21.430
So I've got a couple of
things I'm going to add to it.

00:07:24.290 --> 00:07:27.910
I'm going to crack this egg
and just whisk it a little bit.

00:07:32.620 --> 00:07:36.400
EVAN RICH: And so right now,
you're almost making a batter.

00:07:36.400 --> 00:07:39.730
So if you just put this
into the pan alone,

00:07:39.730 --> 00:07:41.687
you could slowly cook
it and the starches

00:07:41.687 --> 00:07:44.020
would help bring it together,
and it would kind of work.

00:07:44.020 --> 00:07:49.150
But to make this, we're trying
to make almost like a cake.

00:07:49.150 --> 00:07:54.310
So less of a crispy
potato pancake,

00:07:54.310 --> 00:07:59.540
but more of an actual
pancake with potatoes in it.

00:07:59.540 --> 00:08:01.504
SARAH RICH: So I
added some salt to it.

00:08:01.504 --> 00:08:03.920
Anytime you season something,
I don't know if you noticed,

00:08:03.920 --> 00:08:05.920
but I seasoned up
high and I seasoned

00:08:05.920 --> 00:08:08.350
everything instead of just
throwing a big clump in there

00:08:08.350 --> 00:08:09.940
and then going from there.

00:08:09.940 --> 00:08:12.220
You want to really try
to get your seasoning

00:08:12.220 --> 00:08:14.860
all over the place so that
you can incorporate it really

00:08:14.860 --> 00:08:15.725
evenly.

00:08:15.725 --> 00:08:18.550
If you throw your big clump
in there and mix it up,

00:08:18.550 --> 00:08:21.370
you'll mix it in there, but
this is just a better way

00:08:21.370 --> 00:08:23.500
to really incorporate it evenly.

00:08:23.500 --> 00:08:27.280
This is just a little
cream of tartar.

00:08:27.280 --> 00:08:30.420
And the egg.

00:08:30.420 --> 00:08:33.890
EVAN RICH: The cream of tartar
just helps stabilize the egg

00:08:33.890 --> 00:08:39.530
and make it more of a
cohesive package, I guess.

00:08:39.530 --> 00:08:43.549
It's not that necessary, but
we just do it because we're--

00:08:43.549 --> 00:08:46.250
SARAH RICH: Helps to keep the
egg from being super liquidy,

00:08:46.250 --> 00:08:47.210
I guess.

00:08:47.210 --> 00:08:48.890
And then this is wonder flour.

00:08:48.890 --> 00:08:51.260
So wonder flour is a
special kind of flour

00:08:51.260 --> 00:08:55.010
that it doesn't clump the
way regular flour does.

00:08:55.010 --> 00:08:56.840
So it works really
nicely here so you

00:08:56.840 --> 00:08:58.640
can avoid some of
that clumpyness

00:08:58.640 --> 00:09:00.920
that you can get from flour.

00:09:00.920 --> 00:09:03.610
You can find it in pretty
much all grocery stores.

00:09:03.610 --> 00:09:06.470
It is really not hard to find.

00:09:06.470 --> 00:09:10.070
But if you don't find it and you
just want to use regular flour,

00:09:10.070 --> 00:09:10.904
you can do that too.

00:09:10.904 --> 00:09:12.403
EVAN RICH: So it's
the type of flour

00:09:12.403 --> 00:09:14.470
that you would get if
you're making gravy.

00:09:14.470 --> 00:09:17.150
And at the end, instead
of putting AP flour

00:09:17.150 --> 00:09:20.864
in which will clump,
you put it in at the end

00:09:20.864 --> 00:09:23.030
and it thickens your gravy
up without having to make

00:09:23.030 --> 00:09:25.610
a roux or anything like that.

00:09:25.610 --> 00:09:29.840
So it just helps absorb
and it doesn't clump up.

00:09:29.840 --> 00:09:32.655
SARAH RICH: What do
you think, more egg?

00:09:32.655 --> 00:09:34.050
EVAN RICH: Yeah.

00:09:34.050 --> 00:09:35.213
Yeah, looks good.

00:09:35.213 --> 00:09:37.570
SARAH RICH: OK.

00:09:37.570 --> 00:09:38.320
I'm just checking.

00:09:38.320 --> 00:09:39.480
EVAN RICH: I'm the
sous-chef here,

00:09:39.480 --> 00:09:41.021
I don't know why
she's asking me, OK?

00:09:41.021 --> 00:09:41.780
[LAUGHS]

00:09:41.780 --> 00:09:42.696
SARAH RICH: All right.

00:09:42.696 --> 00:09:44.233
So that's all mixed
really nicely.

00:09:44.233 --> 00:09:47.520
I don't know if you can see.

00:09:47.520 --> 00:09:49.230
So whenever you have
something like this

00:09:49.230 --> 00:09:51.600
that it's got
something raw in it,

00:09:51.600 --> 00:09:54.570
whether it's a meatball or
hamburger, you've got raw meat

00:09:54.570 --> 00:09:56.670
or you've got raw egg
and you don't really

00:09:56.670 --> 00:09:59.400
want to taste it like this to
see if it's seasoned properly,

00:09:59.400 --> 00:10:01.110
you can just cook
a little bit of it

00:10:01.110 --> 00:10:04.110
first and then taste it
yourself, see what you think.

00:10:04.110 --> 00:10:08.590
Add more salt if you
need, or not if you don't.

00:10:08.590 --> 00:10:09.360
EVAN RICH: OK.

00:10:09.360 --> 00:10:12.420
So with this dish,
with everything we do,

00:10:12.420 --> 00:10:13.530
there's a formula, right?

00:10:13.530 --> 00:10:15.460
I'm sure with what
you do every day,

00:10:15.460 --> 00:10:17.670
you have a formula
of how to execute

00:10:17.670 --> 00:10:19.000
things and stuff like that.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:25.440
So with our cooking, there are
a few formulas that we use.

00:10:25.440 --> 00:10:27.060
So one is flavor base.

00:10:27.060 --> 00:10:30.090
So sweet, salty, acidic,
and bitter, right?

00:10:30.090 --> 00:10:33.600
So mixing these flavors
together in a dish

00:10:33.600 --> 00:10:36.150
really help bring out
flavors, but there's also

00:10:36.150 --> 00:10:38.010
a textural thing.

00:10:38.010 --> 00:10:42.700
So creamy, crunchy,
creamy and crunchy

00:10:42.700 --> 00:10:44.280
are usually my
balance, and then just

00:10:44.280 --> 00:10:46.240
kind of everywhere in between.

00:10:46.240 --> 00:10:48.280
So the potato kind of
has a mix of all that.

00:10:48.280 --> 00:10:50.460
But we're also going to
add another layer of it

00:10:50.460 --> 00:10:53.760
with some potato chips, OK?

00:10:53.760 --> 00:11:00.170
So it just brings
another layer of flavor

00:11:00.170 --> 00:11:02.470
and another layer of
complexity, right?

00:11:02.470 --> 00:11:05.470
So part of making
dishes interesting

00:11:05.470 --> 00:11:08.740
is bringing these
layers of complexity.

00:11:08.740 --> 00:11:12.220
And keeping it simple
is what we try and do,

00:11:12.220 --> 00:11:15.100
and texture brings
another layer.

00:11:15.100 --> 00:11:17.890
And the way that we're going
to cook these potato chips,

00:11:17.890 --> 00:11:21.010
it just brings another
flavor to the sweet potato

00:11:21.010 --> 00:11:24.800
that help elevate the dish.

00:11:24.800 --> 00:11:26.900
So I'm just slicing
these on the mandolin.

00:11:26.900 --> 00:11:30.580
So basically making sweet
potato chips, real simple.

00:11:30.580 --> 00:11:33.520
I mean, it's very easy.

00:11:33.520 --> 00:11:35.530
We've got a pot of
oil on the stove.

00:11:35.530 --> 00:11:39.372
That's probably about
low to medium high.

00:11:39.372 --> 00:11:40.330
SARAH RICH: 350, about.

00:11:40.330 --> 00:11:41.680
EVAN RICH: 350.

00:11:41.680 --> 00:11:44.350
You don't want to go too hot,
because it'll burn the chips.

00:11:44.350 --> 00:11:46.480
So sweet potatoes have
a lot of sugar in them,

00:11:46.480 --> 00:11:49.870
so too hot on the pan,
too hot in the frying oil

00:11:49.870 --> 00:11:51.980
will burn them really quickly.

00:11:51.980 --> 00:11:54.480
So you want to go low and slow.

00:11:54.480 --> 00:12:01.020
And so the oil is
just barely bubbling

00:12:01.020 --> 00:12:03.170
when I drop everything in there.

00:12:03.170 --> 00:12:05.830
And so it'll be perfect.

00:12:05.830 --> 00:12:09.570
So I just want to kind
of let them go real slow.

00:12:09.570 --> 00:12:12.170
They'll cook nice and evenly
and they won't really brown up.

00:12:12.170 --> 00:12:15.030
And there is a moment
when they're perfect,

00:12:15.030 --> 00:12:18.330
and then two seconds later,
they're a little too dark.

00:12:18.330 --> 00:12:22.000
SARAH RICH: And I would say,
we give you a temperature guide

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:25.080
and we say about 350, but
just use your instinct.

00:12:25.080 --> 00:12:27.690
As you're cooking, if that
seems to be a little high,

00:12:27.690 --> 00:12:30.220
depends on how much sugar
is in the actual potato,

00:12:30.220 --> 00:12:31.290
they're all different.

00:12:31.290 --> 00:12:34.409
How thick you cut it, all of
those things can affect it.

00:12:34.409 --> 00:12:36.450
So just, maybe you need
to turn it down a little,

00:12:36.450 --> 00:12:38.160
maybe you need to
turn it up a little.

00:12:38.160 --> 00:12:42.900
Don't just take our word
specifically exactly

00:12:42.900 --> 00:12:43.880
to be right.

00:12:43.880 --> 00:12:45.255
EVAN RICH: And so
if you're going

00:12:45.255 --> 00:12:47.460
to make this specific
dish or a dish like it,

00:12:47.460 --> 00:12:49.043
these are something
you can definitely

00:12:49.043 --> 00:12:51.960
make ahead, put them on the
side, and just have them ready.

00:12:51.960 --> 00:12:55.244
Because a lot of the cooking
we do, you cook it to order

00:12:55.244 --> 00:12:56.160
and then you serve it.

00:12:56.160 --> 00:12:57.720
So something like
this, the potato

00:12:57.720 --> 00:12:59.800
pancakes if you're
making this at home,

00:12:59.800 --> 00:13:01.841
you're going to want to
cook the potato pancakes,

00:13:01.841 --> 00:13:03.600
plate them up, serve
them, and eat them.

00:13:03.600 --> 00:13:06.820
You can make the potato pancakes
and reheat them in the oven.

00:13:06.820 --> 00:13:11.010
But the best way to do it
is to cook them, serve them.

00:13:11.010 --> 00:13:13.777
At my grandmother's
house on Sunday,

00:13:13.777 --> 00:13:15.360
my grandmother would
be in the kitchen

00:13:15.360 --> 00:13:18.954
making the potato pancakes and
putting out batches, coming

00:13:18.954 --> 00:13:21.120
back, eating a little bit,
go back into the kitchen,

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:22.450
cook some more potato pancakes.

00:13:22.450 --> 00:13:23.158
SARAH RICH: Yeah.

00:13:23.158 --> 00:13:25.399
EVAN RICH: So depending on
what you're trying to do

00:13:25.399 --> 00:13:27.690
or how many people you're
cooking for, you kind of want

00:13:27.690 --> 00:13:30.210
to just like, OK cool,
I'm going to cook these,

00:13:30.210 --> 00:13:32.910
I'll have everything else
ready, and then we'll

00:13:32.910 --> 00:13:33.845
plate everything up.

00:13:33.845 --> 00:13:35.220
SARAH RICH: But
you can also have

00:13:35.220 --> 00:13:37.950
an oven on a low
temperature with a nice--

00:13:37.950 --> 00:13:41.130
put a pan in there so the pan
gets warm, like a cookie sheet.

00:13:41.130 --> 00:13:44.659
And you can cook one,
two, three, four of these,

00:13:44.659 --> 00:13:46.200
as you cook them
put them in the oven

00:13:46.200 --> 00:13:47.400
so they stay nice and warm.

00:13:47.400 --> 00:13:49.080
You're not heating them,
you're not reheating them,

00:13:49.080 --> 00:13:50.790
you're just keeping
them nice and warm

00:13:50.790 --> 00:13:53.320
and then plate them right
away and send them out.

00:13:53.320 --> 00:13:54.062
EVAN RICH: OK.

00:13:54.062 --> 00:13:55.770
So while she's getting
all the pans ready

00:13:55.770 --> 00:13:57.436
and these are frying,
I'm going to start

00:13:57.436 --> 00:13:58.650
making the salsa verde.

00:13:58.650 --> 00:14:00.480
And so salsa verde,
to me, is one

00:14:00.480 --> 00:14:04.680
of these sauces that
I make very often

00:14:04.680 --> 00:14:08.770
and a bunch of
different versions.

00:14:08.770 --> 00:14:12.090
One of the things we always
like to have on a dish

00:14:12.090 --> 00:14:13.980
is something bright and fresh.

00:14:13.980 --> 00:14:18.030
And a salsa verde, to me, is
one of these things that's

00:14:18.030 --> 00:14:19.620
just really light,
really bright,

00:14:19.620 --> 00:14:24.180
and just brings a really,
really nice element to a dish.

00:14:24.180 --> 00:14:26.652
So you can make it a
bunch of different ways.

00:14:26.652 --> 00:14:28.110
But the way we
usually start it off

00:14:28.110 --> 00:14:31.310
is with some
shallots and garlic.

00:14:31.310 --> 00:14:36.150
And so the texture in this
sauce is important to me,

00:14:36.150 --> 00:14:39.690
so I don't want to mince
things up too much.

00:14:39.690 --> 00:14:44.550
In the cookbook, we tell you to
put it all into the Robot Coupe

00:14:44.550 --> 00:14:45.940
and it works perfect.

00:14:45.940 --> 00:14:49.540
But when you do-- so that's
the Robot Coupe right there.

00:14:49.540 --> 00:14:51.870
So when you do it, you
just want to get everything

00:14:51.870 --> 00:14:56.070
in and quickly pulse
it, like [VOCALIZING],,

00:14:56.070 --> 00:14:59.010
and not break everything
down too soupy.

00:14:59.010 --> 00:15:01.030
So I like to do it by hand.

00:15:01.030 --> 00:15:02.700
And I think when we
made the cookbook,

00:15:02.700 --> 00:15:04.741
we were just trying to
think about the people who

00:15:04.741 --> 00:15:05.860
are cooking at home.

00:15:05.860 --> 00:15:08.070
But if you're not
making too much of this

00:15:08.070 --> 00:15:10.620
or cooking for too many
people, doing it by hand

00:15:10.620 --> 00:15:12.600
is really easy.

00:15:12.600 --> 00:15:14.440
And it shouldn't be a problem.

00:15:14.440 --> 00:15:15.904
So I just mince
up some shallots.

00:15:15.904 --> 00:15:18.320
SARAH RICH: I'm going to stop
you while you're doing that.

00:15:18.320 --> 00:15:18.940
EVAN RICH: Yeah, yeah, go ahead.

00:15:18.940 --> 00:15:19.650
SARAH RICH: I'm going
to go ahead and start

00:15:19.650 --> 00:15:20.550
cooking the pancakes.

00:15:20.550 --> 00:15:22.620
So I've got a little bit
of olive oil and butter

00:15:22.620 --> 00:15:23.910
in the pan.

00:15:23.910 --> 00:15:27.210
I put the olive oil in
first, just to kind of--

00:15:27.210 --> 00:15:29.430
I'm warming up the
olive oil, but it's also

00:15:29.430 --> 00:15:31.309
keeping it kind of
a low temperature

00:15:31.309 --> 00:15:33.600
so that when I add the butter,
there's less of a chance

00:15:33.600 --> 00:15:35.280
that I'm going to
burn the butter.

00:15:35.280 --> 00:15:37.842
I don't want to get
really color on it.

00:15:37.842 --> 00:15:40.050
That can be really good
flavor, but that's not really

00:15:40.050 --> 00:15:41.790
the flavor I'm looking for here.

00:15:41.790 --> 00:15:44.440
But the flavor of the
olive oil and the butter

00:15:44.440 --> 00:15:45.870
will be nice with the pancake.

00:15:45.870 --> 00:15:51.990
So I'm just going to put
some of the mixture in there,

00:15:51.990 --> 00:15:53.070
adjust my temperature.

00:15:53.070 --> 00:15:55.740
A lot of cooking is really just
about adjusting temperature.

00:15:55.740 --> 00:15:59.100
You're constantly like, oh
it's getting a little too warm,

00:15:59.100 --> 00:16:00.240
it's browning on the edges.

00:16:00.240 --> 00:16:04.710
Or it's not warm enough, I need
to go up, I need to go down.

00:16:04.710 --> 00:16:07.980
Don't just turn on the stove and
walk away and say that's right.

00:16:07.980 --> 00:16:10.380
You're constantly
looking and adjusting.

00:16:10.380 --> 00:16:11.700
OK, back to you, Evan.

