00:25:09.170 --> 00:25:10.510
EVAN RICH: OK.

00:25:10.510 --> 00:25:14.830
And so this is a dish
that speaks to right now.

00:25:14.830 --> 00:25:19.420
So right now, the season
is cold and rainy.

00:25:19.420 --> 00:25:24.130
So sweet potatoes-- vegetables
become sweet in the winter

00:25:24.130 --> 00:25:28.420
because they protect
themselves from freezing

00:25:28.420 --> 00:25:33.520
by creating glucose
in themselves,

00:25:33.520 --> 00:25:34.990
which is sweet to us.

00:25:34.990 --> 00:25:37.730
So at night when it's super
cold, they don't freeze.

00:25:37.730 --> 00:25:40.240
And so the sweet potatoes
are great this time of year.

00:25:40.240 --> 00:25:41.950
And then also,
with all the rain,

00:25:41.950 --> 00:25:45.110
all these green vegetables
are starting to come up.

00:25:45.110 --> 00:25:48.070
So this is part of a family
called brassica, which

00:25:48.070 --> 00:25:49.450
is like my favorite vegetable.

00:25:49.450 --> 00:25:54.070
So cauliflower, broccoli,
cabbage, Brussels sprouts,

00:25:54.070 --> 00:25:56.410
and they just have this
great sweet flavor.

00:25:56.410 --> 00:25:58.370
So I love sweet vegetables.

00:25:58.370 --> 00:26:02.020
And sprouting broccoli is--

00:26:02.020 --> 00:26:05.560
I guess you kind of think
of this as a bitter green,

00:26:05.560 --> 00:26:08.550
but actually this time
of year it's super sweet,

00:26:08.550 --> 00:26:10.750
and it is really great.

00:26:10.750 --> 00:26:14.110
So any type of sprouting
broccoli or sprouting vegetable

00:26:14.110 --> 00:26:19.070
like this will really
work for this dish.

00:26:19.070 --> 00:26:22.910
So we just do this real simple.

00:26:22.910 --> 00:26:27.050
We take some boiling
water and some salt.

00:26:27.050 --> 00:26:30.454
And so when you're cooking
green vegetables, the key--

00:26:30.454 --> 00:26:31.870
so when you're in
culinary school,

00:26:31.870 --> 00:26:34.580
they teach you, large amounts
of salted boiling water.

00:26:34.580 --> 00:26:36.590
Large amounts of
salted boiling water.

00:26:36.590 --> 00:26:40.780
So with green vegetables,
the object of cooking them

00:26:40.780 --> 00:26:44.050
is to make them tender
and get them ready to eat.

00:26:44.050 --> 00:26:47.380
But if you put too many in
a pot-- so when they cook,

00:26:47.380 --> 00:26:50.110
they admit some kind of acid.

00:26:50.110 --> 00:26:51.830
I forget the exact name of it.

00:26:51.830 --> 00:26:53.680
But if they're too
much in the pot,

00:26:53.680 --> 00:26:56.830
the acid drips back in and
that turns the vegetable brown.

00:26:56.830 --> 00:26:59.710
Or if you put a lid on
it, the acid drips back in

00:26:59.710 --> 00:27:01.250
and it turns the
vegetable brown.

00:27:01.250 --> 00:27:06.080
So you want to cook them
as quick as possible,

00:27:06.080 --> 00:27:08.757
so that's where the rolling
salted water comes in.

00:27:08.757 --> 00:27:10.840
So the salt brings the
temperature up a little bit

00:27:10.840 --> 00:27:13.720
and it makes the water
a little bit hotter

00:27:13.720 --> 00:27:17.750
than it would without the salt.
And just drop the vegetables in

00:27:17.750 --> 00:27:20.560
and let them cook
really quickly.

00:27:20.560 --> 00:27:23.980
So normally, if you're not
going to use them right away,

00:27:23.980 --> 00:27:26.290
you would have an ice
bath and cool them down.

00:27:26.290 --> 00:27:27.915
But we're going to
use them right away,

00:27:27.915 --> 00:27:30.730
and I'm going to take
it the next step that's

00:27:30.730 --> 00:27:32.150
not in the cookbook.

