00:35:37.022 --> 00:35:38.480
So you mentioned
you have children,

00:35:38.480 --> 00:35:40.580
and I don't know
how old they are.

00:35:40.580 --> 00:35:43.270
But I'm interested in your
current or future approach

00:35:43.270 --> 00:35:46.030
to how you're going to engage
your children with food.

00:35:46.030 --> 00:35:49.510
And the reason I answer
that is, probably

00:35:49.510 --> 00:35:51.070
many mothers and
fathers in the room,

00:35:51.070 --> 00:35:53.794
but we went through
a long time where

00:35:53.794 --> 00:35:55.960
parents had to go back to
work, and it was very hard

00:35:55.960 --> 00:35:58.540
for them to be able to
cook with their kids.

00:35:58.540 --> 00:36:01.420
There's nothing harder than
being chefs, and restaurateurs,

00:36:01.420 --> 00:36:02.710
and cookbook authors.

00:36:02.710 --> 00:36:04.552
How are you going to
factor that in to be

00:36:04.552 --> 00:36:05.760
able to expose your children?

00:36:05.760 --> 00:36:07.780
Or are you going to be like,
kids, stay out of the kitchen,

00:36:07.780 --> 00:36:08.821
find your own profession?

00:36:08.821 --> 00:36:09.940
EVAN RICH: No, no.

00:36:09.940 --> 00:36:12.664
They've got a job waiting
for them washing dishes, OK?

00:36:12.664 --> 00:36:13.830
SARAH RICH: They can't wait.

00:36:13.830 --> 00:36:17.050
EVAN RICH: They're
waiting, just waiting.

00:36:17.050 --> 00:36:19.190
I'll let her go into it.

00:36:19.190 --> 00:36:23.770
But from my view of it,
I mean, everyone always,

00:36:23.770 --> 00:36:26.530
my kids will never cook, no way,
I'm going to push them away.

00:36:26.530 --> 00:36:29.530
I mean, I really love
what I do and I enjoy it.

00:36:29.530 --> 00:36:32.540
I'm not going to push
my kids to do what I do.

00:36:32.540 --> 00:36:34.300
But if they're
interested in it, I'm

00:36:34.300 --> 00:36:36.070
definitely going to
be excited and help

00:36:36.070 --> 00:36:39.670
them navigate through
and develop themselves

00:36:39.670 --> 00:36:43.180
as people who have a great
career and push through it.

00:36:43.180 --> 00:36:47.020
SARAH RICH: So we have two
boys, they're seven and four.

00:36:47.020 --> 00:36:49.600
And everybody always says,
oh, you guys are chefs,

00:36:49.600 --> 00:36:51.550
your kids must eat so well.

00:36:51.550 --> 00:36:53.511
They must be so adventurous
with their eating.

00:36:53.511 --> 00:36:54.010
No.

00:36:54.010 --> 00:36:56.250
They are children, they are
picky just like all children.

00:36:56.250 --> 00:36:57.470
EVAN RICH: They are adventurous
with the dino nuggets.

00:36:57.470 --> 00:36:58.840
SARAH RICH: Yeah.

00:36:58.840 --> 00:37:02.440
So I guess the approach
has really been,

00:37:02.440 --> 00:37:05.050
there are times where I
cook more adventurous stuff

00:37:05.050 --> 00:37:08.517
and I expect that
they at least try.

00:37:08.517 --> 00:37:10.225
And there are other
times where, yeah, we

00:37:10.225 --> 00:37:12.980
eat dino nuggets, or
soup, or whatever.

00:37:12.980 --> 00:37:15.520
But the thing that
we really have found

00:37:15.520 --> 00:37:19.630
is that if you involve them
in the process of cooking,

00:37:19.630 --> 00:37:21.820
they are much more
likely to eat it.

00:37:21.820 --> 00:37:25.900
They get excited about being a
part of doing that, of helping

00:37:25.900 --> 00:37:27.760
you, of having a task.

00:37:27.760 --> 00:37:31.510
It makes them feel
confident and excited to be

00:37:31.510 --> 00:37:32.710
helping mommy or daddy.

00:37:32.710 --> 00:37:35.687
And then they're much more
interested in eating the food.

00:37:35.687 --> 00:37:38.020
EVAN RICH: I have a tendency
to cook a lot of vegetables

00:37:38.020 --> 00:37:40.228
when I'm home cooking, just
because at the restaurant

00:37:40.228 --> 00:37:41.830
I eat pastas and steak.

00:37:41.830 --> 00:37:43.380
You know, I'm tasting
all this stuff.

00:37:43.380 --> 00:37:44.921
And when I come home
for the weekend,

00:37:44.921 --> 00:37:46.379
I usually cook
really light stuff

00:37:46.379 --> 00:37:47.920
that we've just
gotten at the market.

00:37:47.920 --> 00:37:51.790
And one day I made this
cauliflower vegan salad, kind

00:37:51.790 --> 00:37:53.370
of roasted, blah, blah, blah.

00:37:53.370 --> 00:37:56.110
And I had both of the kids
with me the whole time

00:37:56.110 --> 00:37:59.380
cutting tomatoes, or cutting
the onions, and doing this.

00:37:59.380 --> 00:38:03.760
And it's a dish that
normal kids and my kids

00:38:03.760 --> 00:38:06.400
included would like, [GROANS].

00:38:06.400 --> 00:38:08.870
But incorporating them into
the cooking process of it,

00:38:08.870 --> 00:38:11.609
they were so excited, and they
ate like, three bowls of it.

00:38:11.609 --> 00:38:12.400
SPEAKER 1: Awesome.

00:38:12.400 --> 00:38:13.350
Yeah, that's great.

00:38:13.350 --> 00:38:15.308
How many people here have
kids and involve them

00:38:15.308 --> 00:38:16.810
in the kitchen?

00:38:16.810 --> 00:38:17.560
Awesome.

