00:41:38.290 --> 00:41:41.500
Especially for those of us
we come home after a long day

00:41:41.500 --> 00:41:44.830
or it's a busy weekend, what's
a good approach to walking

00:41:44.830 --> 00:41:46.390
into a market and
saying, OK, I'm

00:41:46.390 --> 00:41:47.890
going to make a new
recipe from what

00:41:47.890 --> 00:41:49.306
I see here that
looks really good,

00:41:49.306 --> 00:41:50.740
especially if we're in a rush?

00:41:50.740 --> 00:41:53.590
EVAN RICH: Well, so
keeping it simple, right?

00:41:53.590 --> 00:41:56.759
So I mean, it's easy
for me to be like,

00:41:56.759 --> 00:41:59.050
oh, just go to the market,
see what's good and cook it.

00:41:59.050 --> 00:42:02.890
But really, if you
went to a market

00:42:02.890 --> 00:42:04.600
and saw a bunch of
greens, it's like,

00:42:04.600 --> 00:42:08.890
cool, I'm going to steam
rice, blanch them, saute them,

00:42:08.890 --> 00:42:11.860
season them with a little
shoyu and toasted sesame

00:42:11.860 --> 00:42:12.940
and put it over rice.

00:42:12.940 --> 00:42:15.190
I mean to me, that's delicious.

00:42:15.190 --> 00:42:17.980
And the more experience you have
cooking those type of things

00:42:17.980 --> 00:42:20.162
at home, and just
feeling comfortable,

00:42:20.162 --> 00:42:21.620
I know how to cook
beets, I'm going

00:42:21.620 --> 00:42:23.860
to get a bunch of beets
and maybe just mess

00:42:23.860 --> 00:42:25.180
around a little bit.

00:42:25.180 --> 00:42:28.720
The reason why we do what
we do is just experience,

00:42:28.720 --> 00:42:34.130
like flavor building, technique
in cooking, memories we have.

00:42:34.130 --> 00:42:36.169
And we just build
these things together

00:42:36.169 --> 00:42:37.210
and what they experience.

00:42:37.210 --> 00:42:41.050
So going to the market, it
might be a little difficult

00:42:41.050 --> 00:42:42.710
or daunting at first.

00:42:42.710 --> 00:42:44.790
But it's like, just
keep it simple.

00:42:44.790 --> 00:42:46.540
The food you're going
to get at the market

00:42:46.540 --> 00:42:48.130
is delicious no matter what.

00:42:48.130 --> 00:42:52.570
So a baby cabbage that
you just sear and put

00:42:52.570 --> 00:42:54.190
a little vinaigrette
on, that's great.

00:42:54.190 --> 00:42:55.690
SARAH RICH: I think
all of that goes

00:42:55.690 --> 00:42:58.960
back to what he talked about
at the beginning in terms

00:42:58.960 --> 00:43:02.110
of, we think a lot about
acid, and sweetness,

00:43:02.110 --> 00:43:05.050
and bitterness, and texture.

00:43:05.050 --> 00:43:07.690
Like the example
of the rice dish,

00:43:07.690 --> 00:43:10.150
the rice is sort of
a creamy nuttyness.

00:43:10.150 --> 00:43:11.650
You've got the
greens on top, you've

00:43:11.650 --> 00:43:14.770
got the saltiness
from the soy sauce.

00:43:14.770 --> 00:43:17.920
You've got something a little
crunchy, the sesame is crunchy.

00:43:17.920 --> 00:43:20.170
So if you think in
those terms, what

00:43:20.170 --> 00:43:22.300
is a texture that I
can bring to this?

00:43:22.300 --> 00:43:23.800
It doesn't have
to be complicated.

00:43:23.800 --> 00:43:27.040
You're more building on these
basic flavors and ideas.

00:43:27.040 --> 00:43:27.710
EVAN RICH: Yeah.

00:43:27.710 --> 00:43:30.060
You build your equation
in your head of the things

00:43:30.060 --> 00:43:31.260
you like to eat.

00:43:31.260 --> 00:43:33.450
And then it's like,
cool, instead of broccoli

00:43:33.450 --> 00:43:36.420
I can get collard greens.

00:43:36.420 --> 00:43:38.520
Instead of this I can get that.

00:43:38.520 --> 00:43:41.162
And just think about
the different things.

00:43:41.162 --> 00:43:42.870
SARAH RICH: And it's
trial and error too.

00:43:42.870 --> 00:43:43.994
You will make things that--

