00:44:52.510 --> 00:44:54.010
talking about about our home.

00:44:54.010 --> 00:44:57.820
So it's like, the
cooks, I probably

00:44:57.820 --> 00:45:00.670
see the cooks more
than I see my kids.

00:45:00.670 --> 00:45:03.400
I mean, my kids just learned who
I was maybe a year and a half

00:45:03.400 --> 00:45:04.180
ago.

00:45:04.180 --> 00:45:08.590
They thought I was the grumpy
guy who slept in the back room.

00:45:08.590 --> 00:45:13.489
So it's important to
have a culture that--

00:45:13.489 --> 00:45:14.530
so it's a balance, right?

00:45:14.530 --> 00:45:17.740
So there is a level of
professionalism, drive,

00:45:17.740 --> 00:45:19.660
motivation, and intensity.

00:45:19.660 --> 00:45:22.690
Because we take our
jobs very serious.

00:45:22.690 --> 00:45:25.540
Being a cook in our restaurant
is not a sustainable job.

00:45:25.540 --> 00:45:27.550
You don't take a cook job
and you're like, cool,

00:45:27.550 --> 00:45:29.841
I've got the best job and
this is what I'm going to do.

00:45:29.841 --> 00:45:33.430
It's, I've taken this job
so I can learn, grow, build,

00:45:33.430 --> 00:45:37.480
move on, so that I can
find my path as a chef.

00:45:37.480 --> 00:45:39.310
And so there is a
level of intensity.

00:45:43.030 --> 00:45:44.530
I don't want to say
there's yelling,

00:45:44.530 --> 00:45:46.480
but there is definitely
very straightforward

00:45:46.480 --> 00:45:49.180
blunt conversations of like,
do it like this, I don't care,

00:45:49.180 --> 00:45:50.620
don't talk, go.

00:45:50.620 --> 00:45:53.230
Because in the kitchen,
it moves very quickly.

00:45:53.230 --> 00:45:58.399
When we're cooking for the
guests who are there, it's not,

00:45:58.399 --> 00:45:59.440
cool, we have 20 minutes.

00:45:59.440 --> 00:46:01.120
Re-do that, let's
think about this.

00:46:01.120 --> 00:46:03.350
It's, hey, this dish is
up, there paying for it,

00:46:03.350 --> 00:46:06.400
let's go, it needs to be right.

00:46:06.400 --> 00:46:09.520
There is a level of that where
demeaning someone, or talking

00:46:09.520 --> 00:46:13.197
down, or being a
yeller is horrible.

00:46:13.197 --> 00:46:15.280
It's like, I don't want
that, I don't need someone

00:46:15.280 --> 00:46:16.760
talking to me like that.

00:46:16.760 --> 00:46:19.750
I take the approach of,
I talk to people the way

00:46:19.750 --> 00:46:20.950
I want to be talked to.

00:46:20.950 --> 00:46:24.370
And we have a great environment,
I have a great relationship

00:46:24.370 --> 00:46:25.540
with all of our cooks.

00:46:25.540 --> 00:46:27.070
SARAH RICH: We've
also both worked

00:46:27.070 --> 00:46:30.190
in those kitchens where
people are screaming,

00:46:30.190 --> 00:46:34.150
people are mean to each other,
people sabotage each other.

00:46:34.150 --> 00:46:37.820
It's cutthroat, everybody's
out for everybody else's job.

00:46:37.820 --> 00:46:42.760
And that's not what we want
our kitchen to feel like.

00:46:42.760 --> 00:46:45.710
And like Evan says,
it's very fast paced,

00:46:45.710 --> 00:46:47.530
sometimes you have to
be short with people,

00:46:47.530 --> 00:46:49.360
there's not time to mess around.

00:46:49.360 --> 00:46:53.890
But I think that
aside, I think we have

00:46:53.890 --> 00:46:55.310
created a really nice culture.

00:46:55.310 --> 00:46:57.160
We want our team to
feel like a team,

00:46:57.160 --> 00:46:59.890
we want them to feel like
they're working together.

00:46:59.890 --> 00:47:00.880
They're not working
against each other.

00:47:00.880 --> 00:47:02.629
EVAN RICH: We put a
lot of energy into it.

00:47:02.629 --> 00:47:07.060
Because the longer people
stay, the better you can build.

00:47:07.060 --> 00:47:10.990
I always say to every new cook
who comes in or new person,

00:47:10.990 --> 00:47:11.920
this is the circle.

00:47:11.920 --> 00:47:14.830
If we live in here, we're
joking around, we're having fun,

00:47:14.830 --> 00:47:17.350
we're doing what we need to
do, everyone's progressing--

00:47:17.350 --> 00:47:19.810
SARAH RICH: And as a
diner, you can sense that,

00:47:19.810 --> 00:47:22.330
and you can taste that,
and you can feel that.

00:47:22.330 --> 00:47:25.000
I'm sure you have been to
restaurants where you walk in--

00:47:25.000 --> 00:47:26.160
I know I have--

00:47:26.160 --> 00:47:27.910
and you see the kitchen
and they're like--

00:47:27.910 --> 00:47:29.315
EVAN RICH: Just feel the stress.

00:47:29.315 --> 00:47:30.940
SARAH RICH: They're
scared that they're

00:47:30.940 --> 00:47:31.981
going to get screamed at.

00:47:31.981 --> 00:47:35.740
You see the servers who look
like they hate their lives.

00:47:35.740 --> 00:47:37.960
A guest can feel
that and taste it.

00:47:37.960 --> 00:47:41.044
And you don't want to
create that for anyone.

00:47:41.044 --> 00:47:41.710
EVAN RICH: Yeah.

00:47:41.710 --> 00:47:43.720
I mean, I've actually
learned over the years

00:47:43.720 --> 00:47:47.230
that the more you focus
on the inside culture

00:47:47.230 --> 00:47:50.410
and the enjoyment of the
staff, the better that

00:47:50.410 --> 00:47:52.510
translates to the guest.

00:47:52.510 --> 00:47:55.180
I guess in the beginning, I
was always like, the guest,

00:47:55.180 --> 00:47:57.610
the guest, the guest,
and didn't really think

00:47:57.610 --> 00:48:00.199
about the staff or the
culture and stuff like that.

00:48:00.199 --> 00:48:02.240
And then just over the
years with the experience,

00:48:02.240 --> 00:48:09.070
the more we focus on the
employee culture and enjoyment

00:48:09.070 --> 00:48:11.470
of everything, that
translates even more

00:48:11.470 --> 00:48:14.740
into the guest experience, and
they have an even better time.

00:48:14.740 --> 00:48:17.650
Because at the end of the
day, the server, the cook,

00:48:17.650 --> 00:48:20.110
the manager, the
hostess, the dishwasher,

00:48:20.110 --> 00:48:23.050
everyone is representing us.

00:48:23.050 --> 00:48:26.800
So if they're not representing
us the proper way,

00:48:26.800 --> 00:48:29.140
they're not translating
our vision to you.

00:48:29.140 --> 00:48:31.150
And we want them to be happy.

00:48:31.150 --> 00:48:33.940
And this is our house.

00:48:33.940 --> 00:48:36.910
And so everyone in it is
welcome and happy in it.

00:48:36.910 --> 00:48:40.000
But there definitely gets some
tension moments, you know?

00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:41.980
I mean, we're
married, so we always

00:48:41.980 --> 00:48:44.552
make it awkward sometimes.

00:48:44.552 --> 00:48:46.510
SPEAKER 1: Well, I think
that's the perfect way

00:48:46.510 --> 00:48:48.070
to end our time together.

00:48:48.070 --> 00:48:49.295
We have some food coming out.

00:48:49.295 --> 00:48:50.920
But before the food
touches your hands,

00:48:50.920 --> 00:48:52.600
let's give a last
round of applause.

00:48:52.600 --> 00:48:55.650
[APPLAUSE]

